      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The only number that changes form is uno, which has the feminine form una. Remember the uno loses its -o before a noun. uno must always agree in gender with the noun that follows it, even when it forms part of another number:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["Tiene veintiún años.", "Hay veintiuna casas."],
        "words2": ["She is 21 years old.", "There are 21 houses"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Notice that numbers 21 to 29 are written as one word in modern Spanish. You may come across some older spellings where they appear as separate words:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["veinte y dos", "veinte y ocho"],
        "words2": ["", ""]
      },

      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "A hundred is either cien or ciento depending on the context in which it is used.When it is followed by a plural noun,it is cien: "
      },

      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["cien hombres", "cien casas"],
        "words2": ["100 men", "100 houses "]
      },

      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "When it is followed by another number, it is ciento: "
      },

      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["ciento veintiocho"],
        "words2": ["", ""]
      },

      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The exception to this rule is 100,000,which is cien mil."
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Numbers above 100 are as follows: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "200",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["doscientos"],
        "words2": ["(doscientas before a feminine plural noun"]
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "Similarly:",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": [
          "300",
          "400",
          "500",
          "600",
          "700",
          "800",
          "1.000",
          "2.000",
          "1.000.000"
        ],
        "words2": [
          "trescientos",
          "cuatrocientos",
          "quinientos",
          "seiscientos",
          "setecientos",
          "ochocientos",
          "novecientos",
          "mil",
          "dos mil",
          "un millón"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "It is very easy to combine numbers in Spanish: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "Similarly:",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["105", "256", "389", "1.247", "2.321", "1.750.459"],
        "words2": [
          "ciento cinco",
          "doscientos cincuenta y seis",
          "trescientos ochenta y nueve",
          "mil doscientos cuarenta y siete",
          "setecientos",
          "dos mil trescientos veintiuno ",
          "un millón setecientos cincuenta mil cuatrocientos cincuenta y nueve"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Notice that the only place y occurs is between tens and units.  "
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Note: In numbers a full stop is used to mark off thousands or millions, when in English we would use a comma. The comma is used where we would use the decimal point in English (e.g. 12,6% el doce coma seis por ciento – ‘twelve point six per cent’). "
      }
    ],

    "subCh2": "Telling the time",
    "lessonContentSubCh2": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "If it is on the hour: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "Masculine Singular/Plural",
        "label2": "Feminine Singular/Plural",
        "words1": ["Es la una.", "Son las dos.", "Son las tres."],
        "words2": [
          "It's one o'clock.",
          "It's two o'clock.",
          "It’s three o’clock, etc. "
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Note the use of es in the case of one o’clock and son in all other cases. "
      },

      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "To express a number of minutes past the hour y is added to the above, followed by the appropriate number:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": [
          "Son las ocho y veinte.",
          "Son las tres y cinco.",
          "Es la una y diez."
        ],
        "words2": [
          "It is twenty past eight.",
          "It is five past three.",
          "It is ten past one."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "As in English 'quarter past' and 'half past' are usually expressed with words rather than with the numbers themselves: "
      },

      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["Son las doce y media.", "Son las siete y cuarto."],
        "words2": ["It's half past twelve. ", "It's quarter past seven."]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "To express a number of minutes before the hour menos is used in the same way as y:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["Son las tres menos cinco.", "Es la una menos cuarto."],
        "words2": ["It's five minutes to three. ", "It's quarter to one. "]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "If you want to specify the part of the day you are referring to you can add to the above expressions: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["de la mañana", "de la tarde", "de la noche "],
        "words2": ["morning", "afternoon, roughly until dark", "after dark"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Instead of son las doce de la noche you can say es medianoche and instead of son las doce de la mañana you can say es mediodia. "
      },

      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "You cannot add fractions to midnight or midday like you do in English: 'half past midnight' = las doce y cuarto de la noche (not *medianoche y cuarto)."
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "If you want to say 'at' a certain time as opposed to 'it is…', you just replace es or sonwith a:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["a las diez y media de la mañana", "a medianoche"],
        "words2": ["at 10.30 a.m. ", "at midnigh"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Two useful expressions to remember are sobre (about) and en punto (precisely):"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["sobre las ocho", "a las dos en punto"],
        "words2": ["about eight o'clock", "at two on the dot "]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The 24-hour clock is used in the same circumstances as in English, for example when announcing departure times of trains or planes:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["Las trece veintiséis"],
        "words2": ["thirteen twenty-six "]
      }
    ],

    "subCh3": "Telling the time",
    "lessonContentSubCh3": [
      {
        "type": "subchapter",
        "text": "Days of the Week"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The days of the week are as follows:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": [
          "domingo",
          "lunes",
          "martes ",
          "miércoles",
          "jueves",
          "viernes",
          "sábado"
        ],
        "words2": [
          "Sunday",
          "Monday",
          "Tuesday",
          "Wednesday",
          "Thursday",
          "Friday",
          "Saturday"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Notice that capital letters are not used unless the word comes at the beginning of the sentence. "
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The days of the week are all masculine nouns and to say 'on Monday' the definite article el is used: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["el lunes"],
        "words2": ["on Monday"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "To say 'on Mondays' (i.e.regularly, every week) the definite article is used with the plural noun:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["los lunes"],
        "words2": ["on Mondays"]
      },
      {
        "type": "subchapter",
        "text": "Months of the year"
      },

      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": [
          "enero",
          "febrero",
          "marzo",
          "abril",
          "mayo",
          "junio",
          "julio",
          "agosto",
          "se(p)tiembre",
          "octubre",
          "noviembre",
          "diciembre"
        ],
        "words2": [
          "January",
          "February",
          "March",
          "April",
          "May",
          "June",
          "July",
          "August",
          "September",
          "Ocrober",
          "November",
          "December"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "*The Spanish for 'September' can be spelt either with or without the p. The more modern spelling is setiembre. "
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "en is used to say 'in…':"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["en julio"],
        "words2": ["in July "]
      },
      {
        "type": "subchapter",
        "text": "Dates"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "To ask the date you could say either: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["¿Qué fecha es hoy?"],
        "words2": [""]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "To ask the date you could say either: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["Es el dos de mayo."],
        "words2": ["It is the second of May. "]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Or you could say:"
      },

      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["¿A qué estamos?"],
        "words2": [""]
      },

      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "In this case the answer would be:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["Estamos a dos de mayo."],
        "words2": ["It is the second of May."]
      },

      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The first of the month is commonly expressed by el uno de, but el primero is also found. "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["El uno de diciembre.", "El primero de diciembre."],
        "words2": [""]
      },

      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "If you want to add the year to the date, it is normally joined to the date by de:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["El doce de marzo de dos mil uno."],
        "words2": [""]
      }
    ],
